AGI -&nbsp; "The health conditions of the Pope, > which he rested well all night, are basically like those of last night >". That's what Vatican sources report. The Pontiff "has not had respiratory crisis> and continues the usual therapy of these days to cure bilateral pneumonia". The same sources point out that "medical bulletins never talked about sedatives"
For a couple of days > the conditions of the Pontiff were worry.&nbsp;Renal insufficiency, although "initial" and "lief", weighed as a macigno.&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2>Bagnasco, resignation? It seems that there is no reason to hypothesize it
On the news of possible resignation of Pope Francis,» Cardinal Angelo Bagnasco at Rtl 102.5 > answered: "I don't know that, but I think there's no reason to talk about resignation or to hypothesize them. If the world stopped to pray, it is a great thing: a chain of prayer > which rose to the Lord precisely for the Holy Father Francis at this delicate moment."
"According to medical bulletins, the Pope's health conditions are slightly improved.> We continue to pray that it will improve more and more, until complete healing and return to his ministry."
"The whole world, all those who in one way or another participated in this moment of prayer with the rosary, will bring in the heart this experience, which will help to live and to be together better than before. This moment will be repeated, and the continuity of this prayer in the square is another very beautiful sign > and important sign of faith in Jesus and of union around the successor of Peter, the Holy Father Francis. This certainly strengthens our faith and our ecclesial communion >" he concluded.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2 The Twin Chaplain invokes the 'salus' for Francesco</h2>
"Give us today our daily health The word health comes from the Latin salus and has a double meaning, health of the body and salvation of the soul. Let us ask her for us, for those who are admitted to this hospital and for our beloved Pope. Give us the possibility that our Pope may continue to serve the Gospel." This was said by Fr Nunzio Currao, the chaplain of the Gemelli where Pope Francis was admitted from 14 February, at the end of the hour of Eucharistic Adoration in the chapel of the hospital, before the beginning of the Mass. In the moment of prayer, Fr Nunzio prayed for the Pontiff: "Support him at this time of trial and illness" he said invoking the Lord.
<h2>Frate Massimo, Francesco una bussola nel tempo obscure/h2>
"Today we pray in a special way for Pope Francis. He is showing us with this moment of proof that there is an example of evangelical greatness, simplicity, closeness to the last." This was said by Frate Massimo, the Minister General of Minor Friars who have been taking care of these days at the Gemelli Polyclinic and who today celebrated Mass in the hospital chapel. "Let us ask the Lord - he continued proclaiming the homily - that he continues to listen to our prayer so that he sustains Pope Francis. We need it as a compass of a dark time that we are living. We need this compass." "Let's hope for revitalization in spirit and body," he added.&nbsp;
<h2> Continue prayers to the Gemini, "trust in the Lord"</h2>
Continues support for the Pope admitted from 14 February to the Policlinico Gemelli. In the inner chapel first the Adoration and then the Mass. Out there are many faithful, but also many families of people admitted. Many leave a lumino or a flower. Today there is also a group of religious of the Vietnamese association, arrived around 12.30: they remain in prayer, in absolute silence, in front of the statue of Pope John Paul II now become a point of encounter and recollection for many in these particular days. Where the rosary takes place every afternoon. And don Nunzio, chaplain to the Twins, reminds him with a small 'cold' to the press: "I take the statue of John Paul II today afternoon as every day we will make the rosary hoping that journalists let us pray in holy peace do your work but with discretion" he asked. Then he announced that "the day for Mass will be with us Cardinal Vicar Baldo Reina". "We are here for solidarity, affection and trust in the Lord," Father Joseph explained, conversing with AGI before remaining silent for prayer.
